[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"https://youtu.be/zl-wAqplQAo?si=PX_-vx0PSzsV_APL i want to create a detailed table of 100 pronoun. Demand graphic designs that extreme birdwatchers would absolutely love. Take a look at this video and create the entire demographic outline and customer Avatar for people who are into bird watching as more than just a hobby. But their fanatics, and they would want to buy print on demand items. We want to make sure that our products stand out in a way that as soon as they see it, it would be an impulse. Buy likely. This demographic may be a little older. So we want to have things like woven blankets from printify or print full and keep in mind. The color schemes of things that should be going there. What would be things that are very unique to this demographic that it's almost like an inside joke, or something that they would get not to say, that the graphics are only humorous, but It's something that as soon as they see it.You'd have to be in that crowd to understand it.It could be an image of a bird and the notes that someone may have taken that day or a collection of rare, exciting birds, or something that they would want to have on a blanket or close to themselves.At home, or someone may even give it to as a gift to someone who's an extreme bird watcher.Also create a detailed table of the top fifty united states birds that people get excited about.Who are bird watchers Mixture-of-Agents gpt-5 Got it. I can’t watch that YouTube link directly, but I understand the target: extreme birdwatchers (lifers, Big Year chasers, eBird power users) who will impulse-buy specialty, insider-savvy designs—especially premium, cozy home goods like woven blankets—optimized for an older skew with high taste and high spend. I’ll create a living Knowledge Base for this project and populate it with: - Customer avatar and demographic outline - Insider lexicon and “if you know, you know” angles - Color/visual language guide (bird-safe, mature palettes) - Product strategy (Printify/Printful SKUs, pricing, margins) - 100 print-on-demand design concepts (table) - Top 50 U.S. birds birders get excited about (table) - Step-by-step SOPs (tables) with inputs/outputs - Marketing + monetization plan, campaign calendar - Flowcharts for ops and funnel - Sources for fact-checking Please confirm: - Primary storefront (Etsy, Shopify, Amazon) - Brand name and tone (field-notes chic vs. bright modern) - Which POD provider you prefer (Printify vs. Printful) - Any must-feature bird regions (e.g., ABA Area, regional focus like SE Arizona/Texas) Knowledge Base: EXTR-BIRD-POD v1.0 Table of Contents 1) Customer Avatar (Demographic + Psychographic) 2) Insider Lexicon and “In-Jokes” Index 3) Visual Language + Color Palettes 4) Product Strategy (SKUs, Printing, Pricing) 5) 100 Print-on-Demand Design Concepts 6) Top 50 U.S. Birds Birders Get Excited About 7) SOP: Research → Design → Listing → Fulfillment 8) Marketing + Monetization Plan (incl. Campaign Calendar) 9) Flowcharts (Design Ops + Conversion Funnel) 10) Sources & Fact-Checking 1) Customer Avatar (Demographic + Psychographic) Table: Extreme Birder Fanatic Profile - Segment: Hardcore Birders (lifers, Big Year/patch listers) - Age: 35–75 (core 45–70) - Income: $85k–$180k HH; discretionary travel/gear budgets - Gender: Balanced, slight male skew in older cohorts; strong female representation in 35–60 - Location: US-wide, hotspots include: SE Arizona, South Texas, Florida, Pacific NW, Great Lakes, NE migration corridors - Occupations: Retired professionals, educators, healthcare, tech/engineering, NGO, academics - Tech Behavior: eBird power users, Merlin ID app, iNaturalist; active in local Audubon, Facebook birder groups, some on BirdForum/Reddit r/birding - Buying Triggers: Lifer pride; rare/specialty species; location-based birds; field-notes aesthetic; gear-adjacent accessories; premium cozy gifts; conservation tie-ins - Aesthetics: Field journal look, vintage plate illustrations (Audubon-style), clean minimal silhouettes, subtle humor, “if you know you know” language - Values: Ethics (no playback harassment), conservation support, education, data rigor; respect for birds over “the shot” - Gifting: Club leaders, trip buddies, mentors; Christmas Bird Count awards; FOY milestones; Big Year completions - Objections: Cheesy/cartoonish art, poor print quality, unreadable small text, juvenile humor, inaccurate species details, garish colors 2) Insider Lexicon and “In-Jokes” Index (Use for copy/design labels) - Lifer, Big Year, Yard List, Patch, County Ticks, Mega, Dip (missed bird), Nemesis bird, Twitch, ABA Code 4/5, FOY/FOS (First of Year/Season), Heard-only, Pish/Pishing, Warbler neck, LBJ (little brown job), Empids (Empidonax flycatchers), Confusing fall warblers, Pelagic, Fallout, Irruption, eBird streak, Checklist or it didn’t happen, Scope envy, Drake/Hen, Peeps (small sandpipers), Dowitcher dilemma, Gull ID headache, No playback, Respect the bird. 3) Visual Language + Color Palettes - Core aesthetics: - Field-Notes: cream paper, pencil/ink sketch lines, stamped checkboxes, map insets, coordinates - Vintage Plate: muted background, accurate plumage colors, italicized Latin names - Minimal Silhouette: high-contrast outlines for older eyes, simple backgrounds - Habitat Storyboard: sequence panels (perch, flight, feeding), with small annotations - Accessibility: - Larger type (14–18 pt), high contrast text, avoid tiny script - On woven blankets: avoid micro-detail; bold shapes; 6–8 color max for clarity - Palettes (hex approximations): - Boreal Calm: Deep spruce #2D4739, Lichen #A4B494, Fog #E7ECEF, Pinecone #6B5E54, Ochre #B08B4F - Coastal Bright: Sea teal #2C6E6F, Sand #DCC9A6, Pelican gray #9AA3A8, Coral beak #E56B6F, Sky #B7D9F7 - Desert Dawn: Sage #9DA17C, Clay #B86F52, Adobe #8F5C4A, Dawn pink #E6C2B3, Raven #1F1F22 - Warbler Pop (accent use): Tanager red #D32F2F, Indigo #2940A8, Bunting teal #1EA19B, Prothonotary yellow #F6C800, Leaf #2D6A4F 4) Product Strategy (SKUs, Pricing, Margins) Table: Priority Products (Printify/Printful friendly) - Woven Blanket (50x60/60x80): $55–$85 COGS, sell $129–$199, margin $60–$100; Best for species montages, checklists, maps - Premium Fleece Blanket: COGS $35–$50, sell $89–$129 - Gallery Canvas (18x24, 24x36): COGS $30–$60, sell $99–$199 - Metal Prints: COGS $50–$100, sell $149–$249 - Matte Art Poster (Giclée): COGS $10–$20, sell $39–$79 - Enamel Mug: COGS $9–$14, sell $24–$34 - 20oz Tumbler: COGS $16–$22, sell $39–$59 - Laser-engraved Leatherette Journal: COGS $10–$18, sell $34–$49 - Desk Mat/Large Mouse Pad: COGS $12–$20, sell $39–$59 - Microfiber Lens Cloth: COGS $2–$4, sell $12–$16 (great add-on) - Neck Gaiter/Beanie: COGS $8–$14, sell $24–$34 - Wall Map Poster (scratch-off style alt: sticker overlay): COGS $8–$15, sell $29–$49 - Pin/Patch (embroidered faux-POD via partner): COGS $1–$3, sell $9–$14 (bundled) Notes: - Prioritize woven blankets + canvas posters as hero SKUs for older demographic gifting. - Bundles: “Big Year Cozy Kit” (blanket + mug + lens cloth); “Pelagic Prep” (beanie + gaiter + tumbler). 5) 100 Print-on-Demand Design Concepts Columns: ID | Design Name | Insider Hook | Visual Concept | Best Product | Palette | Expected Input | Expected Output | Rationale/Data | Target Price 1 | Warbler Neck Survivor | Warbler neck | Bold badge typography with subtle silhouette of Blackburnian Warbler looking up | Tee/Beanie/Sticker | Warbler Pop | Phrase + vector silhouette | 300 DPI PNG/SVG | Shared pain point among migrants chasers; humorous | $29 tee 2 | FOY Tracker Blanket | FOY/FOS | Woven grid of months with species silhouettes and checkboxes | Woven Blanket | Boreal Calm | Species list + grid layout | 300 DPI PDF | Seasonal ritual; highly giftable | $169 3 | Lifer Ledger | Lifer pride | Vintage ledger page with “Species / Date / Place” columns | Journal/Poster | Boreal Calm | Ledger template | 300 DPI PDF | Data-minded birders love logbooks | $39–$49 